    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p><code>toCharArray</code> followed by <code>Arrays.sort</code> followed by a String constructor call:</p>\n\n<pre><code>import java.util.Arrays;\n\npublic class Test\n{\n    public static void main(String[] args)\n    {\n        String original = \"edcba\";\n        char[] chars = original.toCharArray();\n        Arrays.sort(chars);\n        String sorted = new String(chars);\n        System.out.println(sorted);\n    }\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>EDIT: As tackline points out, this will fail if the string contains surrogate pairs or indeed composite characters (accent + e as separate chars) etc. At that point it gets a lot harder... hopefully you don't need this :) In addition, this is just ordering by ordinal, without taking capitalisation, accents or anything else into account.</p>\n"
